@node "Intro" "Introduction"

   @{u}Introduction:@{uu}

   The @{b}Wasted Time@{ub} is a simple way to measure the time You
   are spending with Your Amiga working every day.

   To add some sense to it, I have added the money-measurement mechanism
   which might be found quite usable some day.

   @{b}Wasted Time@{ub} uses AppMenu solution to be called up by the user,
   and can be controlled by Exchange (or CXCommander) as it become
   commodity.

   It works in background storing information about passed time in
   S: drawer every 5 minutes by default (until you change those values.
   with corresponding @{" ToolTypes " link ToolTypes}.

   Have fun!

@endnode

@node "Disclaimer" "Diclaimer"

   I don't care if You will find some day Your Amiga turned into
   lame pC due to using @{b}Wasted Time@{ub}. So, You're using it on Your own
   risk!

   ...but it should work painless.

@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"

   Simply copy @{b}Wasted Time@{ub} with it's icon into WBStartup.

   Included wastedtime.catalog should be placed in proper Locale's
   drawer.

   In case you encounter problems mastering COPY command, we recommend
   enclosed Installer script, which, when launched by double-click
   is expected to do all needed work for you harmless.

   After this You can restart Your Amiga or start it by clicking the icon.

@endnode

@node "ToolTypes" "TOOLTYPES"

   @{b}Wasted Time@{ub} recognizes following ToolTypes (or CLI arguments as well):

   DISPLAY_MONEY         - permit the displaying of money calculations

   CURRENCY_SIGN = text  - allows You to set CurrencySymbol instead of
                           default Locale's one.

   MINS_PER_UNIT = int   - defines the number of minutes to be passed
                           for one "time unit". Setting this to zero
                           disables money calculations.

   MONEY_PER_UNIT = int  - defines the amount of money to be gained
                           after passing of every "time unit". Setting
                           this to zero disables money caltulations.

   SAVE_EVERY = int      - defines the number of minutes to pass between
                           the savings of information onto HD.
                           Added due to exteded usage of HS_Sleep alike
                           software. Default = 5 mins.

   @{u}@{b}New in v2@{uu}@{ub}

   LOG_FILE = FileName   - lets you override default placement and name
                           of program's logfile (which is S:Wasted.report),
                           with your own.

   SAVE_ON_QUIT          - if you want @{b}Wasted Time@{ub} to save state of
                           wasted counter on exit, just enable this tooltype

   NO_MENU_ITEM          - if you don't like programs adding own menu items
                           to the Workbench's Tools menu, just use this
                           tooltype and the have fun calling Wasted report
                           with hotkey or relaunching program

   @{b}Standard Commodity hotkeys (for beginers)@{ub}

   CX_PRIORITY           - program's priority in internal Commodity list
                           (0 fits almost everyone needs)

   CX_POPKEY             - hotkey you want @{b}Wasted Time@{ub} to react on
                           and open Wasted report window

   CX_POPUP              - this tooltype normally forces to open program's
                           window (if there's any) on startup, but it's
                           ignored by @{b}Wasted Time@{ub} so far
@endnode

@node "Locale" "Locale"

   As released, @{b}Wasted Time@{ub} contains built-in English texts and
   Polish (my native language) catalog 'wastedtime.catalog'.

   You can easily built Your own since I have included the
   file 'wastedtime.cd'.

   If you use polish environment, W.F.M.H. LocalePL, @{b}Wasted Time@{ub}
   will take special care on using proper numerals.

   @{b}NOTE:@{ub} if you want @{b}Wasted Time@{ub} to cares about your
   numerals (in case of exceptions), please let me know.

   Polish version uses @{fg shine}AmigaPL@{fg text} standard, as it is
   used in W.F.M.H.'s LocalePL © Marcin Orlowski which may be taken from
   Aminet @{i}(misc/misc)@{ui} or our support BBS.

   Have fun!

   PS. I have received the swedish translation, but as I lost e-mail of the
       translator (sorry pal), I couldn't ask him for the update...

@endnode

